% ============================================================
\section{Introduction}
% ============================================================

\subsection{What is Agent-Based Modeling?}

An \emph{agent-based model} (ABM) is a computational model in which individual
autonomous entities---agents---interact with each other and with their
environment according to local rules. The population-level dynamics emerge from
these micro-level interactions rather than being specified top-down. Agents can
represent people, animals, firms, particles, or any discrete entity whose
behaviour is governed by rules.

ABMs differ from classical mathematical models in three respects:
\begin{itemize}
  \item \textbf{Discreteness.} Populations consist of integer counts of individuals,
    not continuous densities.
  \item \textbf{Heterogeneity.} Individual agents can differ in state, location,
    and behaviour.
  \item \textbf{Locality.} Interactions occur between agents that are spatially or
    socially proximate, not between population-level aggregates.
\end{itemize}

\subsection{Why Should Statisticians Care?}

The classical tools of mathematical modeling---ordinary differential equations,
compartmental models, mean-field approximations---are familiar to quantitative
scientists. They are tractable and admit analytical results, but they rest on
assumptions that are rarely stated explicitly and often violated in practice.

The ABM offers three things a statistician should find immediately relevant:

\begin{enumerate}
  \item \textbf{Stochastic output.} The ABM is a data-generating process.
    Each run produces a realisation; repeated runs produce a distribution.
    This is the natural language of statistical inference.
  \item \textbf{Finite-population effects.} When populations are small, the
    law of large numbers does not apply. Variance matters, extinction is
    possible, and the ODE's deterministic prediction can be systematically
    wrong.
  \item \textbf{Mechanism transparency.} The model's assumptions are explicit
    rules applied to discrete agents. Misspecification is visible; structural
    changes can be made one rule at a time.
\end{enumerate}

\subsection{The Central Epistemological Tension}

The key intellectual tension running through this course is between two
extrapolation failure modes.

\textbf{False equilibrium.} A model built around a steady state implicitly
assumes the system will remain near that state indefinitely. When the
trajectory approaches a threshold, the model has nothing to say. Ecological
models that assume stable predator-prey cycles cannot predict extinction;
epidemic models built on $\mathcal{R}_0$ cannot predict stochastic fadeout.

\textbf{Apocalypse extrapolation.} A model that captures exponential growth
or power-law connectivity will, extrapolated far enough, predict catastrophe.
Network epidemic models predict near-certain explosive spread for modest
connectivity increases; this extrapolation is credible only within the regime
the model was calibrated on.

Isaac Newton's \emph{Principia Mathematica} \citep{newton1687} is the paradigm
case of successful extrapolation: planetary mechanics obey conservation laws
and exhibit closure and linearity over the relevant time scales and spatial
scales. These conditions---conservation, closure, linearity---are precisely
what ecological and epidemiological systems conspicuously lack.

\textbf{The ABM resolution.} Rather than committing to a point prediction,
the ABM produces a distribution over possible futures. Policy questions are
reframed as hitting-time problems: ``what is the probability of crossing
threshold $X$ before time $T$?'' This is a well-posed statistical question
that ODE models cannot answer.

\subsection{System Dynamics vs Agent-Based Models: a Roadmap}

We develop three paired models: predator-prey, epidemic, and firm-size
dynamics. In each case we implement the standard system-dynamics (ODE)
model first, then build the agent-based counterpart using the same
ecological or epidemiological parameters, then compare outputs.

The comparison is not merely illustrative. Each section identifies exactly
which assumptions the ODE makes, which of those assumptions the ABM relaxes,
and what new phenomena become visible as a result.

% ============================================================
\section{System Dynamics: the Lotka-Volterra Predator-Prey Model}
% ============================================================

\subsection{Model Formulation}

The Lotka-Volterra system \citep{lotka1925,volterra1926} describes two
interacting populations---prey $x(t)$ and predators $y(t)$---via the
coupled ODEs:
\begin{align}
  \frac{dx}{dt} &= \alpha x - \beta x y \label{eq:lv-prey}\\
  \frac{dy}{dt} &= \delta x y - \gamma y \label{eq:lv-pred}
\end{align}
The parameters have the following ecological interpretation:
\begin{itemize}
  \item $\alpha > 0$: per-capita prey birth rate (intrinsic growth in
    the absence of predators).
  \item $\beta > 0$: predation rate (rate at which prey are removed per
    predator--prey encounter).
  \item $\gamma > 0$: per-capita predator death rate (decay in the
    absence of prey).
  \item $\delta > 0$: predator birth rate per prey eaten (conversion
    efficiency of prey into predator offspring).
\end{itemize}

The model has two conserved quantities that together produce closed
orbits: it is Hamiltonian, and the trajectories in $(x, y)$ space are
closed curves around the non-trivial equilibrium.

\subsection{Equilibrium Analysis}

Setting $dx/dt = 0$ and $dy/dt = 0$ in equations~(\ref{eq:lv-prey}) and
(\ref{eq:lv-pred}) yields two fixed points: the trivial equilibrium
$(0, 0)$ and the non-trivial equilibrium.

\begin{proposition}
The non-trivial Lotka-Volterra equilibrium is
\begin{equation}
  x^* = \frac{\gamma}{\delta}, \qquad y^* = \frac{\alpha}{\beta}.
  \label{eq:lv-eq}
\end{equation}
\end{proposition}

\begin{proof}
From $dy/dt = \delta x y - \gamma y = y(\delta x - \gamma) = 0$ with
$y \neq 0$, we obtain $x^* = \gamma/\delta$.  Substituting into
$dx/dt = x(\alpha - \beta y) = 0$ with $x \neq 0$ gives
$y^* = \alpha/\beta$.
\end{proof}

\begin{remark}
The equilibrium~(\ref{eq:lv-eq}) is \emph{neutrally stable}, not
asymptotically stable.  The Jacobian at $(x^*, y^*)$ has purely imaginary
eigenvalues $\pm i\sqrt{\alpha\gamma}$, so trajectories neither converge
to nor diverge from the fixed point: they orbit it on closed curves.
This neutral stability is a structural property of the Lotka-Volterra
system and is not preserved by most perturbations; in particular, it
is not preserved in finite-population realisations.
\end{remark}

\subsection{R Implementation}

We integrate the system using \texttt{deSolve::ode()} with the default
Runge-Kutta solver.

