    traces a closed orbit around the equilibrium $(x^*, y^*) = (30, 5)$.
    The dot marks the initial condition $(x_0, y_0) = (40, 9)$.}
\end{figure}

\subsection{Mean-Field Foundations and Time-Scale Limitations}

The Lotka-Volterra ODE is the mean-field limit of a continuous-time
stochastic birth-death process as the total population $N \to \infty$.
In the stochastic version, each individual birth, death, and predation
event is a Poisson process; the ODE describes the expected trajectory
when $N$ is large enough that fluctuations are negligible.

For finite $N$, the system behaves differently in three important ways.

\textbf{Demographic stochasticity.}  Variance in population size scales
as $1/N$.  Deviations from the ODE trajectory are of order $1/\sqrt{N}$
per unit time.  For the small populations typical in ecological management
contexts---hundreds or thousands of individuals, not millions---this
variance is substantial.

\textbf{Drift and extinction.}  The ODE equilibrium is neutrally stable:
the Hamiltonian structure ensures that the expected trajectory orbits the
fixed point indefinitely.  The stochastic version lacks this conservation
law.  Population sizes execute a random walk around the orbit, and random
walks in one dimension are recurrent \citep{karlin1975}: they revisit every
state, including zero.  In finite time, the stochastic predator-prey system
goes extinct with probability one.

\begin{remark}
The Recurrence Theorem \citep{karlin1975}: a one-dimensional random walk
on the integers is recurrent; it visits every state infinitely often.  The
ODE cannot represent this because it operates on continuous densities; the
ABM makes it directly observable.
\end{remark}

\textbf{Time-scale limitations.}  The ODE is a reliable approximation over
short time horizons, large populations, and trajectories that stay well away
from zero.  Error accumulates as $T$ grows, as $N$ shrinks, and as the
trajectory approaches a boundary.  Conservation management plans built on
ODE cycles implicitly assume the mean-field regime persists indefinitely.
The ABM reframes the policy question: not ``do populations cycle?'' but
``what is the probability of extinction before time $T$?''

\subsection{Activity 1: ODE vs ABM Extinction}
\label{sec:activity1}

\textbf{Teaching point:} The ODE predicts survival at any positive parameter
value; the ABM reveals finite extinction probability.

\textbf{Instructions.}  Open \texttt{demo/demo\_lotka\_volterra.R} and navigate
to the \texttt{ACTIVITY 1} comment.

\begin{enumerate}
  \item Run the ODE with \texttt{params\_low\_alpha} (prey birth rate
    $\alpha = 0.02$).  Plot the trajectory.  Does prey reach zero?
    What does the ODE predict long-run?
  \item Run \texttt{find\_abm\_extinction\_probability()} with the same
    parameters and \texttt{n\_runs = 20}.  What fraction of ABM runs go extinct
    before step 500?  Why does the ODE not predict this?
  \item Vary \texttt{width} from \texttt{10L} to \texttt{50L}.  How does
    extinction probability change with grid size?
  \item \textbf{Extension:} Vary $\alpha$ from 0.02 to 0.20 in steps of
    0.02.  For each value, run 10 ABM replicates and compute extinction
    probability.  Plot extinction probability vs $\alpha$.  Is there a
    sharp threshold or a gradual transition?
\end{enumerate}

% ============================================================
\section{System Dynamics: the ISR Epidemic Model}
% ============================================================

\subsection{Model Formulation}

We adopt the ISR ordering: Infected, Susceptible, Recovered.  This
unconventional labelling is deliberate---it keeps the focus on the
infected compartment, which drives the dynamics, and prevents students
from confusing compartment order with mechanistic flow.

Let $I(t)$, $S(t)$, $R(t) \in [0,1]$ denote the fractions of the
population that are infected, susceptible, and recovered, with
$I + S + R = 1$.  The system evolves as:
\begin{align}
  \frac{dI}{dt} &= \beta I S - \gamma I \label{eq:isr-I}\\
  \frac{dS}{dt} &= -\beta I S \label{eq:isr-S}\\
  \frac{dR}{dt} &= \gamma I \label{eq:isr-R}
\end{align}
with parameters:
\begin{itemize}
  \item $\beta > 0$: transmission rate (contacts per unit time $\times$
    probability of transmission per contact).
  \item $\gamma > 0$: recovery rate ($1/\gamma$ is the mean infectious
    period).
\end{itemize}

\subsection{The Basic Reproduction Number and Herd Immunity}

The basic reproduction number $\mathcal{R}_0$ is the expected number of
secondary infections caused by a single infectious individual introduced
into a fully susceptible population.

\begin{proposition}
For the ISR model with $S(0) \approx 1$:
\begin{equation}
  \mathcal{R}_0 = \frac{\beta}{\gamma}.
\end{equation}
The epidemic grows (i.e.\ $dI/dt > 0$ initially) if and only if
$\mathcal{R}_0 > 1$.
\end{proposition}

\begin{proof}
At $t = 0$ with $I(0) = \epsilon \approx 0$ and $S(0) \approx 1$:
\[
  \frac{dI}{dt}\bigg|_{t=0} = \beta \epsilon S(0) - \gamma \epsilon
  = \epsilon(\beta S(0) - \gamma) \approx \epsilon(\beta - \gamma).
\]
This is positive iff $\beta > \gamma$, i.e.\ $\mathcal{R}_0 = \beta/\gamma > 1$.
\end{proof}

\begin{proposition}[Herd Immunity Threshold]
The fraction of the population that must be immune to prevent epidemic growth is:
\begin{equation}
  p_c = 1 - \frac{1}{\mathcal{R}_0}.
\end{equation}
\end{proposition}

The default parameters ($\beta = 0.3$, $\gamma = 0.05$) give
$\mathcal{R}_0 = 6$, comparable to measles.  This produces a dramatic,
clearly peaked epidemic curve suitable for instruction.

\subsection{R Implementation}

<<isr-run-model>>=
@

<<isr-summary>>=
@

\subsection{Epidemic Curve and Final Size}

\begin{figure}[H]
  \centering
<<isr-time-series, fig.height=4>>=
@
  \caption{ISR ODE epidemic curve with $\mathcal{R}_0 = 6$.  The infected
    fraction (plum) peaks at approximately 52.8\% then declines as the
    susceptible pool is exhausted.  The final epidemic size (total fraction
    ever infected, $= R(\infty)$) is approximately 99\%.}
\end{figure}

\subsection{Mean-Field Foundations and Time-Scale Limitations}

The ISR ODE is the $N \to \infty$ limit of a stochastic SIR process on a
complete graph---where every individual can contact every other individual
with equal probability.  The homogeneous mixing assumption is equivalent
to assuming the contact network is a complete graph.

Three limitations follow from this:

\textbf{Stochastic fadeout.}  When $\mathcal{R}_0 > 1$ in a large
deterministic population, an epidemic always takes off.  In a finite
population, a single infected individual may recover before infecting
anyone: the epidemic dies out by chance.  The probability of this
stochastic fadeout can be approximated by a branching process argument
\citep{bartlett1955, anderssonbritton2000}: the probability that the
epidemic goes extinct is approximately $(1/\mathcal{R}_0)^{I_0}$, where
$I_0$ is the initial number of infected individuals.

\textbf{Contact heterogeneity.}  Real contact networks are not complete
graphs.  High-degree nodes (super-spreaders) have disproportionate impact
on transmission; removing them requires targeting the network structure,
not just reducing $\mathcal{R}_0$.  The epidemic threshold on a
heterogeneous network is determined by the spectral radius of the
next-generation matrix, not by $\mathcal{R}_0$ alone
\citep{diekmann1990}.

\textbf{Policy timing.}  Intervention timing depends critically on where
the epidemic is on its curve.  The ODE gives a single deterministic
trajectory; the ABM gives a distribution.  The mean and the variance of
peak timing both matter for policy.

% ============================================================
\section{Agent-Based Models: Predator-Prey}
% ============================================================

\subsection{From ODEs to Agents}

The Lotka-Volterra ODE describes population-level flow rates.  The ABM
replaces these continuous flows with discrete agents following local rules.
The key changes are:
\begin{itemize}
  \item Prey and predators become individual sheep and wolves with positions,
    energy levels, and survival states.
  \item Interactions are local: a wolf can only eat a sheep that occupies
    the same grid cell.
  \item Reproduction is probabilistic: each agent reproduces with a fixed
    probability per tick when its energy exceeds a threshold.
  \item Energy dynamics replace the ODE's instantaneous birth-death flows:
    each agent gains or loses energy from eating, starving, and reproducing.
\end{itemize}

The macro-level dynamics---population cycles, extinction---emerge from these
micro-level rules without being programmed explicitly.

\subsection{Model Rules}

\textbf{Environment.}  A toroidal grid of \texttt{width} $\times$
\texttt{height} cells.  Toroidal wrapping (opposite edges connect) avoids
boundary effects.  Agent movement uses a Moore neighbourhood: eight adjacent
cells plus the current cell.

\textbf{Sheep} execute the following steps each tick:
\begin{enumerate}
  \item Move to a randomly chosen Moore-neighbourhood cell (including
    current cell).
  \item Gain \texttt{sheep\_gain\_from\_food} energy (baseline = 4; with
    grass extension: only on grown cells).
  \item Lose 1 energy (metabolic cost).
  \item If energy $>$ \texttt{sheep\_reproduce\_threshold} and a uniform
    draw $< \texttt{sheep\_reproduce}$: create an offspring at the same cell,
    each receiving half the parent's energy.
  \item Die if energy $\leq 0$.
\end{enumerate}

\textbf{Wolves} execute the following steps each tick:
\begin{enumerate}
  \item Move to a randomly chosen Moore-neighbourhood cell.
  \item Lose 1 energy.
  \item If any sheep occupies the current cell: eat one, gaining
    \texttt{wolf\_gain\_from\_food} energy (baseline = 20).
  \item If energy $>$ \texttt{wolf\_reproduce\_threshold} and a uniform
    draw $< \texttt{wolf\_reproduce}$: create an offspring.
  \item Die if energy $\leq 0$.
\end{enumerate}

All agents are stepped in uniformly random order each tick, preventing
systematic first-mover advantage.

\subsection{R Implementation}

The model is implemented using R6 classes from the \texttt{R6} package.
The \texttt{PredatorPreyModel} class holds the grid, the agent lists, and
the step logic.

<<pp-run-model>>=
@

<<pp-summary>>=
@

\subsection{Comparison with the ODE}

\begin{figure}[H]
  \centering
<<pp-vs-ode, fig.height=4>>=
@
  \caption{Left: Lotka-Volterra ODE on a 200-unit time horizon.  Right:
    predator-prey ABM on a 20$\times$20 grid (seed = 18, 300 ticks).
    The ABM shows qualitatively similar oscillations but with greater
    amplitude variance and eventual wolf extinction.  The ODE predicts
    stable cycles indefinitely; the ABM reveals finite extinction risk.}
\end{figure}

\begin{figure}[H]
  \centering
<<pp-time-series, fig.height=4>>=
@
  \caption{ABM predator-prey time series (20$\times$20, seed = 18, 300 steps).
    Two complete boom-bust cycles are visible.  Running to step 341 shows wolf
    extinction as the depleted sheep population can no longer sustain the
    wolf cohort.}
\end{figure}

\subsection{Finite-Population Effects and Extinction Risk}

The ABM makes explicit what the ODE conceals.  Extinction is not a
parameter-driven event---it is a stochastic consequence of finite
population size.  On a 20$\times$20 grid with the default parameters,
100\% of 20 independent replicates go extinct within 500 steps, even
though the ODE predicts indefinite cycling.

<<pp-extinction-demo, cache=TRUE>>=
@

The mean time to extinction ($\approx 192$ steps across 20 replicates)
provides a natural analogue to the hitting-time framing discussed in
Section~\ref{sec:activity1}: with probability 1, the stochastic process
eventually crosses the zero boundary that the ODE never approaches.

From a statistical perspective, the ABM output is a distribution over
trajectories, not a point prediction.  The relevant summary is not
``the population at time $T$'' but ``the distribution of time to
extinction'' or ``the distribution of peak wolf count.''

\subsection{Activity 2: Spatial Density and Finite-Population Effects}
\label{sec:activity2}

\textbf{Teaching point:}  The mean-field assumption is a density
assumption.  Holding population constant and varying grid size isolates
spatial density as the variable.

\textbf{Instructions.}  Open \texttt{demo/demo\_predator\_prey.R} and
navigate to the \texttt{ACTIVITY 2} comment.

\begin{enumerate}
  \item Run the three models (sparse 100$\times$100, medium 50$\times$50,
    dense 20$\times$20) with fixed $n_\mathrm{sheep} = 100$ and
    $n_\mathrm{wolves} = 25$.  Which grid size produces dynamics closest
    to the ODE?
  \item Use \texttt{plot\_abm\_ode\_comparison()} to overlay all three ABM
    trajectories on the ODE.  At what density do they diverge most?
  \item Run each grid size 10 times (seeds 1--10).  At which grid size does
    extinction probability first exceed 10\%?
  \item \textbf{Extension:} Does the ODE give any warning that extinction
    is coming?  What would a statistician need to observe to distinguish
    ``near-extinct'' from ``stable cycle'' in real data?
\end{enumerate}

% ============================================================
\section{Agent-Based Models: ISR Epidemic}
% ============================================================

\subsection{From Compartments to Individuals}

The ISR ODE tracks fractions; the pandemic ABM tracks individual people.
The key change is that infection is a \emph{local} event: a susceptible
person becomes infected only if an infected person occupies their
Moore neighbourhood.  In a well-mixed grid, this local rule approximates
the ODE's homogeneous mixing assumption, but with finite-population effects
intact.

\subsection{Model Rules}

\textbf{Person} agents follow these ISR rules each tick (applied
synchronously from a tick-start snapshot):
\begin{itemize}
  \item If in state $S$: for each of the (up to 8) Moore-neighbourhood
    cells containing an $I$ agent, become $I$ with probability $\beta$.
    The compound probability for $k$ infected neighbours is
    $1 - (1 - \beta)^k$.
  \item If in state $I$: transition to $R$ with probability $\gamma$.
  \item If in state $R$: remain $R$ (no re-infection).
\end{itemize}
After state updates, all agents move to a random Moore-neighbourhood cell.
Synchronous updates (all state changes applied from a tick-start snapshot)
ensure that mid-tick state changes do not cascade within a single step.

\subsection{R Implementation}

<<pandemic-run-model>>=
@

<<pandemic-summary>>=
@

\subsection{Comparison with the ODE}

\begin{figure}[H]
  \centering
<<pandemic-vs-ode>>=
@
  \caption{Left: ISR ODE epidemic curve (single deterministic trajectory).
    Right: mean ABM infected fraction across 10 replicates (plum line)
    with $\pm 1$ SD shading.  The ODE and ABM mean agree qualitatively,
    but the ABM reveals run-to-run variance that the ODE cannot represent.}
\end{figure}

\subsection{What the Well-Mixed Assumption Is Really Doing}

The pandemic ABM on a 20$\times$20 grid is a well-mixed model in
disguise: with 400 agents moving randomly on the torus, every agent
is in every other agent's neighbourhood within a few steps.  The ABM
approximates the ODE's complete-graph contact structure.

The key insight is that ``well-mixed'' is not a property of the biology;
it is a property of the \emph{model}.  The ABM makes this explicit by
giving the contact structure (a grid with Moore neighbourhood movement) a
concrete representation.  Replacing the grid with a heterogeneous network
relaxes the assumption in a way that the ODE cannot: the contact
structure is a model component, not a background assumption.

\subsection{Activity 3: Stochastic Variation in Epidemic Outcomes}
\label{sec:activity3}

\textbf{Teaching point:}  The ODE gives one epidemic curve; the ABM gives
a distribution.  Statistical thinking---summarising a distribution, not
reading off a point---is the right framework for ABM output.

\textbf{Instructions.}  Open \texttt{demo/demo\_isr.R} and navigate to
the \texttt{ACTIVITY 3} comment.

\begin{enumerate}
  \item Run the pandemic model 10 times using \texttt{lapply()}.  Call
    \texttt{summarise\_runs()} and examine the distribution of
    \texttt{peak\_I} and \texttt{R0\_empirical}.
  \item Call \texttt{plot\_epidemic\_comparison()} to overlay the mean ABM
    trajectory on the ODE.  Does the ODE peak fall within the ABM
    distribution?
  \item What does the variance in \texttt{peak\_I} imply for policy
    decisions based on the ODE peak infected fraction?
  \item \textbf{Extension:} Increase \texttt{initial\_infected\_fraction}
    to 0.05.  Does variance increase or decrease?  What does this imply
    about epidemic prediction early vs.\ late in an outbreak?
\end{enumerate}

% ============================================================
\section{Extension: Social Networks and Super-Spreaders}
% ============================================================

\subsection{The Well-Mixed Assumption Revisited}

The well-mixed assumption is a complete-graph assumption: every
susceptible individual is equally likely to contact every infected
individual.  Real contact networks are sparse and heterogeneous.
A small fraction of high-degree individuals---super-spreaders---accounts
for a disproportionate share of transmission.

The Barab\'{a}si--Albert (BA) preferential attachment model
\citep{barabasi1999} generates networks with a power-law degree
distribution $P(k) \propto k^{-\gamma_\mathrm{net}}$ that match the
empirical structure of many real-world contact networks.

\subsection{Barab\'{a}si--Albert Networks and Degree Heterogeneity}

The BA algorithm begins with a small seed graph and adds nodes one at
a time.  Each new node attaches $m$ edges to existing nodes, with
attachment probability proportional to degree (preferential attachment).
The resulting degree distribution follows a power law with exponent
approximately $-3$ regardless of $m$.

The model is constructed via:
\begin{verbatim}
igraph::sample_pa(n = n_agents, m = n_edges_per_new_node, directed = FALSE)
\end{verbatim}
Super-spreaders are defined as agents with degree above the 90th
percentile of the degree distribution.

\subsection{R Implementation}

<<network-run-model>>=
@

<<network-summary>>=
@

