\subsection{Super-Spreader Seeding}

Activity 4 introduces a model parameter, \texttt{seed\_hubs}, that
controls whether the initially infected agents are drawn from the
highest-degree nodes rather than uniformly at random.  This isolates
the \emph{seeding location} effect from the \emph{network structure}
effect.

\begin{figure}[H]
  \centering
<<network-hub-seeding, fig.height=4>>=
@
  \caption{Epidemic curves with random seeding (left) vs hub seeding
    (right).  Identical parameters and network structure; only the
    identity of the initially infected agents differs.  Hub seeding
    typically produces a faster-rising epidemic because infected
    agents immediately have many susceptible contacts.}
\end{figure}

\subsection{Statistical Implications: Why $\mathcal{R}_0$ Is Not Enough}

On a heterogeneous network, the epidemic threshold is determined not
by $\mathcal{R}_0 = \beta/\gamma$ but by the spectral radius of the
next-generation matrix \citep{diekmann1990}.  On a complete graph, the
next-generation matrix reduces to a scalar and its spectral radius
equals $\mathcal{R}_0$.  On a heterogeneous network, the threshold is
lower when variance in degree is high, and the final epidemic size
depends on the degree distribution, not just its mean.

\begin{remark}
The apocalypse extrapolation failure mode applies directly here.
Network epidemic models can predict near-certain explosive spread for
modest increases in connectivity.  This extrapolation is credible only
within the regime the model was calibrated on.  Real contact networks
adapt when individuals change behaviour in response to epidemic risk;
the structural assumptions break down precisely when the policy is
most aggressive.
\end{remark}

\subsection{Activity 4: Hub Seeding and Epidemic Shape}
\label{sec:activity4}

\textbf{Teaching point:}  On a heterogeneous network, who gets infected
first matters as much as how many.

\textbf{Instructions.}  Open \texttt{demo/demo\_pandemic.R} and navigate
to the \texttt{ACTIVITY 4} comment.

\begin{enumerate}
  \item Compare the epidemic curves from \texttt{seed\_hubs = FALSE} and
    \texttt{seed\_hubs = TRUE}.  Which produces a faster-rising epidemic?
    Which produces a higher peak?
  \item Examine the super-spreader and non-super-spreader attack rates for
    each seeding strategy.  How do they differ?
  \item What does this imply for early containment policy (contact tracing,
    quarantine)?
  \item \textbf{Extension:} Run both seeding strategies 10 times each.
    Does hub seeding always produce a faster epidemic, or does stochastic
    variation sometimes reverse the result?  At what value of $m$
    (network connectivity) does seeding strategy matter most?
\end{enumerate}

% ============================================================
\section{Extension: Grass and Carrying Capacity}
% ============================================================

\subsection{Adding a Third Trophic Level}

The baseline predator-prey ABM gives sheep unlimited food: they gain
energy every tick regardless of local conditions.  This is equivalent
to an unbounded carrying capacity.  The grass extension adds a finite
food supply: sheep gain energy only from cells with grown grass; eaten
grass must regrow over \texttt{grass\_regrowth\_time} ticks before it
can be consumed again.

The grass layer introduces a mechanistic carrying capacity that is
absent from the baseline model.  In the Lotka-Volterra ODE, carrying
capacity must be added as an explicit term (the logistic Lotka-Volterra
system); in the ABM, it emerges from the local interaction rule.

\textbf{Grass rules:}
\begin{itemize}
  \item Each cell is either grown (grass present) or bare.
  \item At each tick, bare cells count down their regrowth timer;
    cells whose timer reaches zero become grown.
  \item A sheep on a grown cell eats the grass (cell becomes bare,
    timer resets to \texttt{grass\_regrowth\_time}).
  \item A sheep on a bare cell does not gain energy from food;
    it loses 1 net energy per tick instead of gaining 3.
\end{itemize}

\subsection{R Implementation}

\texttt{PredatorPreyGrassModel} inherits from \texttt{PredatorPreyModel}
and overrides only the \texttt{initialize()}, \texttt{step()}, and
\texttt{run()} methods.  All wolf and sheep agent logic is reused.

<<grass-run-model>>=
@

<<grass-summary>>=
@

