% ============================================================
\section{Firm Size and Heavy-Tailed Distributions}
% ============================================================

\subsection{The Empirical Regularity}

\citet{axtell2001} demonstrated that the distribution of US firm sizes
(measured by number of employees) follows a power law over nearly six
orders of magnitude.  This regularity, known as Zipf's law, has proven
remarkably robust across time periods, countries, and industries: the
size of the $r$-th largest firm is approximately proportional to
$r^{-1}$.

\subsection{Power Laws, Zipf's Law, and the Pareto Distribution}

A random variable $X$ follows a \emph{power law} with exponent $\alpha$
if its complementary CDF satisfies:
\begin{equation}
  P(X > x) \propto x^{-(\alpha - 1)}, \quad x \geq x_{\min}.
\end{equation}
Equivalently, the density is $f(x) \propto x^{-\alpha}$ for
$x \geq x_{\min}$.  The special case $\alpha = 2$ (Zipf's law) gives a
CCDF that declines as $1/x$, corresponding to the rank-size regularity.

The maximum-likelihood estimator for $\alpha$, given $x_{\min}$, is:
\begin{equation}
  \hat{\alpha} = 1 + n\left[\sum_{i=1}^n \ln \frac{x_i}{x_{\min}}\right]^{-1}
  \label{eq:mle-alpha}
\end{equation}
where $n$ is the number of observations above $x_{\min}$
\citep{clauset2009}.  The \texttt{poweRlaw} package implements the full
Clauset et al.\ methodology, including data-driven selection of
$x_{\min}$ and goodness-of-fit via a KS test.

\subsection{Why Top-Down Models Fail at Long Time Scales}

Standard industrial organisation models predict stable size distributions
around equilibrium.  The empirical distribution is heavy-tailed and
non-Gaussian, which no equilibrium model generates convincingly.

The time-scale argument is decisive: firm dynamics---entry, growth,
merger, exit---operate on decade-long horizons.  No mean-field
approximation is credible at these scales.  The ``equilibrium trap''
is an instance of the false-equilibrium failure mode: assuming the
system will remain near a stable size distribution ignores the drift
and boundary-crossing that dominates long-run dynamics.

\subsection{Local Interaction as a Generative Mechanism}

\citet{axtell2001} showed that a simple ABM in which firms grow through
local employee recruitment---agents move between firms based on
effort and payoff comparisons---generates the observed power-law
distribution from micro-level behaviour.  The power law is not assumed;
it emerges from the interaction rules.  This is the prototype ABM
explanatory argument: a parsimonious local rule generates a
macro-level regularity that no aggregate model predicted.

\subsection{Fitting and Interpreting the Power-Law Exponent}

<<axtell-load-census>>=
@

<<axtell-fit>>=
@

\begin{figure}[H]
  \centering
<<axtell-plot, echo=FALSE>>=
@
  \caption{US Census firm-size distribution on log-log axes.  The dashed
    line shows the fitted power law ($\hat{\alpha}$ as estimated by MLE
    above $x_{\min}$).  An approximately linear log-log relationship over
    several orders of magnitude is consistent with Zipf's law.}
\end{figure}

