% ============================================================
\section{Discussion: ABM as a Statistical Modeling Paradigm}
% ============================================================

\subsection{The Epistemological Thread Revisited}

We began with a tension: false equilibrium vs.\ apocalypse extrapolation.
Every model we built illustrated one or both failure modes.

The Lotka-Volterra ODE predicts stable cycles that persist indefinitely.
This is false equilibrium: in finite populations, the stochastic version
drifts toward the absorbing boundary at zero.  The ABM makes the
extinction probability directly observable.

The network epidemic model predicts explosive spread for modest
connectivity increases.  This is apocalypse extrapolation: the model
is extrapolated into an intervention regime it was never calibrated on,
and its structural assumptions (static network, constant $\beta$) break
down precisely when the policy is most aggressive.

Newton's laws work because planets conserve energy, operate in a closed
system, and experience no feedback between the measurement and the
measured \citep{newton1687}.  Ecological and epidemiological systems
have none of these properties.  The ABM does not solve this problem;
it makes it honest.

\subsection{Strengths and Limitations of ABM}

\textbf{Strengths:}
\begin{itemize}
  \item Natural representation of discrete individuals, heterogeneity,
    and local interaction.
  \item Output is a distribution: supports Bayesian updating, uncertainty
    quantification, and scenario analysis.
  \item Extensions are modular: adding a new mechanism is adding a new
    rule, not restructuring an ODE system.
  \item Extinction, thresholds, and rare events are representable.
\end{itemize}

\textbf{Limitations:}
\begin{itemize}
  \item Computational cost: each run is a simulation; many runs are
    needed for distributional summaries.
  \item Identifiability: ABMs typically have more parameters than can
    be identified from available data.
  \item No analytical tractability: equilibria, stability, and
    sensitivity analysis require simulation rather than algebra.
  \item Verification: emergent behaviour can be surprising; careful
    testing is essential (see the ghost-eating and energy-timing bugs
    documented in \texttt{Caddena.md}).
\end{itemize}

\subsection{Calibration and Identifiability}

ABM calibration---fitting parameters to observed data---is an active
research area.  Common approaches include:
\begin{itemize}
  \item \textbf{Approximate Bayesian Computation (ABC):} draw parameters
    from the prior, run the ABM, accept parameter values whose simulated
    summary statistics are close to the observed data.
  \item \textbf{History matching:} iteratively rule out regions of
    parameter space that are inconsistent with observed data.
  \item \textbf{Emulation:} replace the expensive ABM with a fast
    Gaussian process surrogate fitted to a design of simulation runs.
\end{itemize}

Identifiability remains a fundamental challenge: many different
parameter combinations may produce indistinguishable output distributions.
This is not a failure of the ABM methodology; it reflects genuine
non-identifiability in the underlying process.

\subsection{When to Use ABM vs.\ ODE vs.\ Statistical Models}

\begin{itemize}
  \item Use an \textbf{ODE} when: populations are large, contact is
    homogeneous, the time horizon is short enough that stochastic
    drift is negligible, and analytical tractability is needed.
  \item Use an \textbf{ABM} when: populations are small, contact is
    heterogeneous (network structure matters), the policy question
    involves rare events or thresholds, or mechanistic transparency
    is required.
  \item Use a \textbf{statistical model} when: the goal is prediction
    from data rather than mechanistic understanding, the process is too
    complex to model from first principles, or calibrated uncertainty
    quantification is the primary deliverable.
  \item The three approaches are complementary.  A well-designed
    empirical workflow uses ODE analysis to identify parameter regimes,
    ABM to probe finite-population and heterogeneity effects, and
    statistical models to link both to data.
\end{itemize}

\subsection{Further Reading}

Key references for each module:
\begin{itemize}
  \item Lotka-Volterra: \citet{lotka1925}, \citet{volterra1926}.
  \item ISR epidemic: \citet{kermack1927}.
  \item Stochastic processes and recurrence: \citet{karlin1975}.
  \item Stochastic epidemic extinction: \citet{bartlett1955},
    \citet{anderssonbritton2000}.
  \item Network epidemic threshold: \citet{diekmann1990}.
  \item BA networks: \citet{barabasi1999}.
  \item Firm-size power law: \citet{axtell2001}.
  \item Power-law fitting: \citet{clauset2009}.
\end{itemize}

